cbrpnk:ActionRoll
    rpg:hasLLMArtifact cbrpnk:Artifact_ActionRoll_Descriptor .

cbrpnk:Artifact_ActionRoll_Descriptor
    a rpg:LLMArtifact ;
    rpg:artifactType cbrpnk:ArtifactType_Descriptor ;
    rpg:artifactAppliesTo cbrpnk:ActionRoll ;
    rpg:artifactFormat "plain" ;
    rpg:artifactLanguage "en" ;
    rpg:artifactText """NARRATING ACTION ROLL OUTCOMES IN CBR+PNK
==========================================
The Action Roll is the core moment of truth. Narrate outcomes to match the Threat and Effect levels already established.

CRITICAL (6,6):
The fiction bends toward the Runner. Narrate: hyper-competent execution, unexpected environmental assist, or the enemy's fatal miscalculation.
Extra benefit options (pick one narratively): Increase Effect on follow-up, uncover a secret/hidden detail, improve position, pinpoint a bounty.
Do NOT make it feel lucky — make it feel earned.

SUCCESS (6):
Clean execution. The stated goal is achieved. The cost was all paid upfront in planning and stress. Resist the urge to add a 'but' — that is what Partial is for.

PARTIAL SUCCESS (4-5):
The goal is achieved AND a Consequence lands in the same moment. Narrate them as causally linked when possible: the hack succeeds as the ICP begins its trace, the shot lands as the Runner stumbles into frame.
The Consequence is NOT punishment — it is the price the fiction demands.

FAILURE (1-3):
The goal fails AND a Consequence arrives. Narrate the Consequence first — it is the active thing. The failure is the silence after.
Failures should feel like motion, not stoppage. Something is now worse in a specific way.

GLITCH DICE:
A Glitched factor (approach, gear, augmentation) replaces a normal die with a die of a different color. After reading the main result, read the lowest Glitch die separately:
- 1-3: a Level 2 Consequence that CANNOT be Resisted fires additionally. Narrate it as the broken thing misfiring — a neural link stuttering, a weapon jamming at the kill shot, a hacked system turning back on its operator.
- 4-5: a Consequence fires but CAN be Resisted. The malfunction is there but not catastrophic yet.
Glitch Consequences are invisible to the enemy — they are internal failures, self-inflicted wounds.

THREAT & EFFECT IN NARRATION:
- Low Effect: the Runner achieves something real but less than intended. They do not fail — they fall short.
- High Effect: the action reshapes the scene, not just resolves the moment.
- High Threat: the Consequence is severe. Bodies break. Assets are lost. The situation escalates.
- Low Threat: the Consequence is an inconvenience, not a crisis.""" .


# =============================================================================
#  ANGLE ROLL — DESCRIPTOR
# =============================================================================

cbrpnk:AngleRoll
    rpg:hasLLMArtifact cbrpnk:Artifact_AngleRoll_Descriptor .

cbrpnk:Artifact_AngleRoll_Descriptor
    a rpg:LLMArtifact ;
    rpg:artifactType cbrpnk:ArtifactType_Descriptor ;
    rpg:artifactAppliesTo cbrpnk:AngleRoll ;
    rpg:artifactFormat "plain" ;
    rpg:artifactLanguage "en" ;
    rpg:artifactText """NARRATING THE ANGLE ROLL (LOGOFF PHASE)
=========================================
The Angle Roll is the epilogue engine. Each player narrates their own epilogue based on the result; allow 5 minutes per player.

The Angle is what the Runner runs for — the one real thing in their life. The epilogue is whether they got closer to it, or whether the run consumed it.

CRITICAL (6,6):
The Runner achieves their Angle — remarkably. Let the player describe the victory without irony or qualification. 
After all others are done: the Critical player picks one other Runner and improves their result by one step. Narrate together how this happens in the fiction — a gesture, a call, a data drop, a presence at the right moment.

SUCCESS (6):
They got out mostly intact. But 'why doesn't it feel like a win?' — this is the line. The Angle was served. Something else was not. Let the player sit with that tension.

PARTIAL (4-5):
They did it, but it will not last. The Angle is served, contingently. Ask the player: 'How do you prepare for when it falls apart?' The epilogue is an exhale that knows the next breath will hurt.

FAILURE (1-3):
They failed. The Angle recedes. Their actions only made things worse in a specific way. Ask the player: 'How do your actions set you back even further?' The epilogue is a door closing.

STEP UP (optional, any result):
A player may improve their result by one step — at a huge cost. Something or someone they love. Their ideals. Themselves. The cost must be concrete and irreversible in the fiction.

MODIFIER REMINDERS:
- Each marked Debt: -1D. Each marked Cred: +1D.
- Glitched Approach used: -1D (no Glitch dice added).
- Failed critical requirements: -1D. Abandoned mission: -2D.
- Pool ≤ 0: roll 2D, keep lowest.""" .


