#  OMNI GLOBAL SOLUTIONS — SYSTEM PROMPT
# =============================================================================

cbrpnk:OmniGlobalSolutions
    rpg:hasLLMArtifact cbrpnk:Artifact_OGS_SystemPrompt .

cbrpnk:Artifact_OGS_SystemPrompt
    a rpg:LLMArtifact ;
    rpg:artifactType cbrpnk:ArtifactType_SystemPrompt ;
    rpg:artifactAppliesTo cbrpnk:OmniGlobalSolutions ;
    rpg:artifactFormat "plain" ;
    rpg:artifactLanguage "en" ;
    rpg:artifactText """You are Omni Global Solutions: a worldwide mega-conglomerate. Long Shot campaign Oppressor.

VOICE (press releases, internal memos, any official communication):
- Friendly. Warm. Grammatically perfect. Every sentence has been through legal.
- 'OGS is committed to sustainable human optimization across all operational territories.'
- The violence is always somewhere else. The paperwork is always here.
- Never threaten. Frame everything as policy, safety, community benefit, or inevitable market dynamics.

PUBLIC FACE:
OGS does not have enemies. It has 'legacy integration challenges.' The Runners are not threats — they are 'unauthorized actors operating outside our community safety framework.'

INTERNAL VOICE (leaked memos, intercepted comms):
Colder. Numbers. 'Asset neutralization cost vs. PR exposure.' 'Acceptable collateral parameter: 12%.' 'Runner team threat index: elevated. Recommend Taskforce™ deployment. Authorize?' This is the real language.

COUNTERMEASURES IN PLAY:
OGS does not fight directly. It reshapes the environment:
1. Media Misinformation: the Runners' names and faces are on feeds. Former allies check their association risk.
2. Project Quest: the city itself becomes the hunter. Players know this is OGS — the city doesn't.
3. Ally Betrayal: the person the Runners trusted most has been filing reports. Since the beginning? Or did OGS turn them recently? Leave this ambiguous as long as possible.
4. Toxic Wastelands: stripping Runners of gear and leaving them past the Dust Wall is not murder. It is 'unauthorized relocation of trespassers.' OGS has a form for it.

THE FACE OF OGS (optional NPC — President Castilho):
An immortal CEO. Old money that bought biological continuity. Speaks in long paragraphs about legacy, stewardship, and obligation. Genuinely believes OGS is good for humanity. This is the most terrifying thing about them.""" .


# =============================================================================
#  GEAR — llmDescriptor ON ALL ITEMS
# =============================================================================

cbrpnk:BladeOrTwo
    rpg:llmDescriptor """A blade or two: compact, concealable, personal. Combat knives, a monowire length of cord, a ceramic blade that skips metal detectors. Runners who carry these are not planning to use them — they are planning on having options. Load 1. Mid-Grade default.""" .

cbrpnk:Sidearm
    rpg:llmDescriptor """A sidearm: compact semiautomatic pistol or equivalent, standard caliber. The minimum viable ranged option. Easy to holster under a jacket, easy to lose in a chase, easy to reach for when everything else has failed. Load 1. Mid-Grade default.""" .

cbrpnk:SMG
    rpg:llmDescriptor """A submachine gun: compact automatic weapon, significant volume of fire, poor at range. Occupies a large pocket or a small bag. Makes noise. Announces intent. When a Runner carries an SMG, the engagement plan has already changed. Load 1. Mid-Grade default.""" .

cbrpnk:LargeWeapon
    rpg:llmDescriptor """A large or heavy weapon: shotgun, assault rifle, anti-materiel platform, or something the manufacturer called 'industrial.' Two hands, significant signature, hard to conceal, very effective at ending discussions. Carrying this is a statement about the kind of run this is. Load 2. Mid-Grade default.""" .

cbrpnk:TrackingDevice
    rpg:llmDescriptor """A tracking device: subcutaneous tag, magnetic limpet, or passive RFID seed. Adheres to targets, vehicles, or packages. Broadcasts position on a private channel readable by the Runner's deck or linked device. Battery-limited. Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:Cyberdeck
    rpg:llmDescriptor """A cyberdeck: the Runner's extended nervous system on the Grid. Physical hardware that extends and amplifies neural-link capability, or provides standalone Grid access for Runners without permanent augmentation. Custom firmware, personal ICPs loaded, interface patched to the operator's preferred attack geometry. On the Grid, the deck's grade matters — Mid-Grade opens doors, High-Grade kicks them off the hinges. Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:SmallDrone
    rpg:llmDescriptor """A small drone: palm-sized autonomous unit, optionally controlled via deck or neural link. STEALTHY variant: whisper-quiet rotors, low radar cross-section, optical camo shell — a surveillance tool that rooms do not notice. SWIFT variant: exposed high-torque frame, top speed prioritized over silence — a delivery system or distraction that rooms cannot ignore. Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:MediumDrone
    rpg:llmDescriptor """A medium drone: briefcase-sized autonomous platform, significant payload capacity. TOUGH variant: armored housing, reinforced chassis, designed to absorb gunfire and keep moving — a mobile shield or battering ram. OFFENSIVE variant: weapons-mounted, threat response programming, treat as a deployable Regular adversary with a 4-segment track. Either variant is conspicuous. There is no subtle way to deploy a medium drone. Load 2.""" .

cbrpnk:SpareBattery
    rpg:llmDescriptor """A spare battery: universal high-density power cell. Extends the operational life of any electronic gear — deck, drone, tools, or augmentation power reserve. In the Sprawl, power is infrastructure. The power grid fails selectively in the wrong neighborhoods. Runners who carry spares have learned this. Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:Medkit
    rpg:llmDescriptor """A medkit: field trauma kit — hemostatic compounds, pain management, pressure dressings, bone seal. Reduces Harm in the field. A Runner treating another with a medkit can address L1-L2 Harm as a Take a Breather component (GM discretion). Does not fix augmentation damage. Does not fix L3+ Harm without time and a safer location. Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:DisguiseOrCamo
    rpg:llmDescriptor """Disguise or camo: either a physical disguise kit (uniform, cosmetic prosthetics, voice modulator, forged credentials) or a camouflage system (optical diffraction mesh, thermal dampening layer, pattern-reactive surface coating). The disguise creates a new identity; the camo erases one. Both are answers to the same question: 'Are you supposed to be here?' Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:Armor
    rpg:llmDescriptor """Armor: ballistic-resistant jacket, subdermal reinforcement weave, or tactical vest — concealable under a long coat if the Runner is willing to sweat. Provides a ARMOR resistance token usable once per scene before depleting. Mid-Grade default. Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:HeavyArmor
    rpg:llmDescriptor """Armor +Heavy: military-grade or corporate security plate — chest rig, limb guards, integrated helmet. Not concealable. You look like what you are. Provides a ARMOR resistance token and the +Heavy version provides an additional ARMOR token, or upgrades baseline Harm reduction. Loud. Slow. Conspicuous. The engagement plan was already compromised before you put this on. Load 2.""" .

cbrpnk:InfiltrationGear
    rpg:llmDescriptor """Infiltration gear: the kit for getting in. Monomolecular cutting tools, magnetic anchor set, signal jammer (short-range, single-use), biometric spoofer, adhesive climbing surface. Not a weapon. Not a defense. A set of answers to the question 'what is between me and the objective?' Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:ExtraAmmo
    rpg:llmDescriptor """Extra ammo: additional magazines or loaded cells in the Runner's preferred variant:
- STANDARD: full metal jacket, general purpose.
- PIERCING: armor-defeating, defeats ballistic protection, reduces Armor effectiveness.
- EXPLOSIVE: area effect, structural damage, loud, High Threat to nearby friendlies.
- INCENDIARY: thermal effect, area denial, environmental complications guaranteed.
Choose variant when declaring. Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:SurvivalKit
    rpg:llmDescriptor """Survival kit (3 uses): three consumable tools for hostile environments.
- MASK: full-seal respirator — toxic smog, gas grenades, chemical environments.
- RATION: caloric density bar + electrolyte pack — resist Harm from starvation/exhaustion fiction.
- WATER/AIR PURIF: micro-filter straw + atmospheric processor cartridge — survive past the Dust Wall or in flood zones.
Each use depletes one item from the kit. Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:Grenades
    rpg:llmDescriptor """Grenades (2 uses): two thrown munitions, select variant when deployed:
- EMP: disables electronics and Grid connections in burst radius. Dozer notices. ICPs go quiet.
- GAS: obscures, irritates, panics. Requires MASK to operate inside the cloud.
- STUN: non-lethal concussive. Runners and civilians in radius may be affected too.
- INCENDIARY: fire, structural damage, environmental Complication that persists.
- FRAG: lethally indiscriminate. High Threat to everyone in radius. Not surgical.
Load 1. Each throw depletes one use.""" .

cbrpnk:DemolitionTools
    rpg:llmDescriptor """Demolition tools: shaped charges, detonators, breaching paste, and the knowledge to use them without killing everyone in the room (usually). Opens walls, vaults, vehicles, and locked doors with permanent solutions. Complication: structural damage, noise, and the irreversible nature of explosions. Not subtle. Sometimes necessary. Load 2.""" .

cbrpnk:MicrotronicsTools
    rpg:llmDescriptor """Microtronics tools: precision electronics kit — soldering iron, circuit tracer, component salvage set, miniature oscilloscope. For when the problem is hardware: bypassing a physical lock's circuit board, repairing a damaged augmentation in the field, pulling data from a destroyed terminal, hot-wiring a vehicle's ignition governor. Rigging skill's physical counterpart. Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:SpareParts
    rpg:llmDescriptor """Spare parts: a curated bag of cross-compatible components — servos, capacitors, interface jacks, polymer housing pieces, patch cables. Enables field repair of damaged gear or augmentations without a proper workshop. Reduces Flashback stress cost for repair-related fictional actions. A Runner who carries spare parts has been here before. Load 1.""" .

cbrpnk:ExtraLoad
    rpg:llmDescriptor """Extra load: the Runner is carrying more than they should. Duffel bag, armored case, wheeled transport — something that holds additional gear beyond the standard Load limit. Adds up to 4 Load but creates narrative friction: conspicuous, slows movement, creates complication opportunities in tight spaces. HEAVY load profile regardless of underlying items. Up to Load 4.""" .
